<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://www.telusplanet.net/public/caber9/knight2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Descent</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">     I could feel the thick hemp of the rope through my Iksar scaled gloves as I carefully lowered myself over the edge of the pit leading to the fabled Skyshrine.   <br>
<br>
The ten-foot square pit is partially covered over with growing vines and weeds that spring up between the cracks of the rough-hewn granite.  <br>
<br>
Immediately below me unseen, Rizerok is inching further into the growing darkness, the dark elf easily supporting himself despite the hundred pounds of plate armor he wears.  <br>
<br>
The others, below Rizerok, also invisible, make their way down the four hundred or so feet into the unknown.  Their groans and grunts, while faint, can be heard coming up the shaft.  Oopola the Wizard and Zupa the mage unaccustomed to such physical exertion in the humid chamber, rest to catch their breaths every twenty feet or so.  Any slip-up here would mean certain death at the bottom.<br>
<br>
“Is everyone here?” asks Jinjin in a serious tone.  The usually affable gnome places all kidding aside when lives are on the line.  The tension in the air is palpable.<br>
“Aye” I say as I drop the last ten feet to the floor.<br>
“Here”<br>
“Here”<br>
“Aye”<br>
“Here” chime in the others together.<br>
“Oopola, uncover your Greater lightstone and let’s see what we have” says Jinjin<br>
<br>
The pulsating light from the GLS reveals a room ten feet by ten feet with a large oak door in one wall.  The floor is littered with the bones of unwary trespassers who either fell from the rope, or failed to notice the grown-over pit at the top.  There is a heavy silence in the air.<br>
<br>
Making sure everyone is still invisible by the semi-transparent effect offered by the see invisible spell, Jinjin motions Oopola to re-cover the light source and to follow him to the door.  The sounds of bones crunching under foot as we make our way to the door seem unnaturally loud in the eerie silence.<br>
<br>
“Remember what I told you” starts Jinjin in a hushed whisper.<br>
“Please listen carefully and do exactly as I say and we’ll get what we’ve come for.  From what Gayla has told me, this should lead to an anteroom with a portcullis that we need to go through.  We need to get past the two sentries at the front and then I’ll consult the map Gayla made for me. Everyone ready?” <br>
<br>
Jinjin’s meaty little hand is lost in the two foot ornate handle of the large oak door.  Pulling with all his considerable might, the door at first would not move, the massive bronze hinges refusing to budge for mere mortals.  <br>
Moving to gain a purchase on the handle with Rizerok, the three of us manage to pull the five inch thick door open a crack.  <br>
<br>
The gush of air through the crack is akin to opening a vault that has been sealed for years, and brings with it a familiar odor.  <br>
Though seasoned veterans, the smell of dragons sends a shiver down each of our spines.  The hot heavy odor, unmistakably dragon, is a reminder of how careful we must be in here.<br>
<br>
Filing through the door single file, I bump into Jobrien on the other side.<br>
“What the..” I mutter before I look up and see what has stopped the cleric in his tracks, a look of fascination in the high-elf’s eyes.<br>
<br>
Dwarven slaves cut Skyshrine’s smooth granite walls into the rock face centuries earlier.  The polished walls rise hundreds of feet into the darkness.  We have emerged into an enormous room lit only by two massive braziers that flank each side of the fifty foot black-iron portcullis that is centered in the wall.<br>
<br>
Jinjin, motioning us to remain quiet, urges us to follow him across the several hundred feet of empty space to the portcullis.  <br>
“I don’t understand it” whispers Jinjin suddenly stopping fifty feet from the entranceway.<br>
“Gayla said that there were guards, but I see no sign of them”<br>
“Well something is or was here” replies Jobrien nodding towards the carpet of bones, armor and weapons gleaming in the faint light of the braziers.<br>
“Something’s not right, but I can’t place it” offers Rizerok<br>
“Me feel like me being watched” says Zupa under her breath.<br>
“Well let’s move before our invis’ wear off” I say trying to sound calm<br>
“Follow” says Jinjin once again moving towards the portcullis.<br>
<br>
We carefully pick our way past the remains of countless adventurers whose bodies have been around so long that armor and weapons have virtually rotted away in the hot, humid air leaving nothing but shining bones.  The true majesty of Skyshrine is revealed the closer you get to its door.  Staring up, one cannot help but feel small and inconsequential beside the mammoth structure.  This place was not made for man.<br>
<br>
As we pass the braziers, someone steps on a bone creating a splintering sound that barely carries over the noise of the flickering flames.  It was perhaps Jinjin’s uncanny senses that saved us. <br>
<br>
Motioning everyone to stop, Jinjin stands motionless for what seems like minutes.  Slowly turning our heads to follow Jin’s gaze, we stare in astonishment as the rock wall itself moves beside the portcullis.  Imperceptible at first until its glowing red eyes open, the stone golem is perfectly camouflaged against the material from which it was created. <br>
<br>
Standing a full twenty feet at the shoulder, the stone golem’s arms end in fists the size of barrels.  The Sentry takes a methodical step forward and then turns and stops, huge chiseled muscles rippling, glowing red eyes searching, but finding nothing.  We can feel every step the golem takes.  Its ponderous weight sending shock waves through the stone floor into our plated boots.<br>
<br>
Turning back towards the portcullis, Jinjin almost starts walking again before he notices that another sentry has appeared silently ten feet away from us from the opposite side.  How could a monster that size move so quietly?<br>
<br>
Stuck between the two suspicious golems, our only way now was forward.  <br>
<br>
The sound of the great mechanism that opens the portcullis cuts through the silent blackness.  Oopola startled by the clank lets out a small startle of surprise.  The gate ever so slowly inches its way upwards revealing a polished granite hallway.  The shrill screech of a drake echoes down the hallway, sounding much to close for comfort.<br>
<br>
“Zalarez” whispers Jinjin <br>
Gayla had warned him that the Gatekeeper of Cobalt Scar could show up unannounced.<br>
<br>
What else can go wrong thought Jinjin.<br>
<br>
“I’m losing invis” says Rizerok quietly.<br>
